Boxplot analysis of continous independent variables¶
    

  • Age - average is 40.9 years old, with a positive skew due to mean (40.9) > median (39). There are some outliers above Q3 + 1.5*IQR, but for age that is expected
    • 

  • Balance - some accounts with negative balance which may indicate an overdraft, with a positive skew due to mean (1362) > median (448). There are some outliers above Q3 + 1.5IQR, as well as below Q1 - 1.5IQR. For balance this is expected to have a wide range of balances
    • 

  • Day - contact day of the month ranges from 1st to 31st of the month, meaning campaign was consistent throughout the month
    • 

  • Duration - mean (258 seconds) > median (180 seconds), indicates a positive skew for the duration of last contact. A minimum of 0 seconds indicates that < 25% of clients did not answer attempts at contacting them. Maximum was 4918 seconds indicating that some customers had some queries to be answered hence the longer duration. There are some outliers above Q3 + 1.5*IQR. Makes sense to replace outliers with the "maximum" value
    • 

  • Campaign - number of contacts ranges from 1 to 63, meaning every client was contacted at least once, but others significantly more which indicates outliers or possible data collection errors, as average is 3 compared to maximum of 63. There are some outliers above Q3 + 1.5*IQR
    • 

  • PDays - with a upper quartile of -1 & maximum of 871, indicates the that majority (>75%) of clients have not been contact recently or period has been greater than 900 days. Probable to best impute -1 entries with the mean
    • 

  • Previous - upper percentile of 0 indicates the that majority (>75%) of clients have not been contacted in previous campaign. There are some outliers above Q3 + 1.5*IQR
    •

Pie and Bar Chart analysis of continous independent variables¶
    

  • job - clients with blue-collar and management are the most at 20% each, with less than 5% each of retired, self-employed, entrepreneur, unemployed, housemaid, student, unknown
    • 

  • marital - majority of clients are married (61%), 28% are single and 11.5% are divorced
    • 

  • education - most clients have secondary education (51%), followed by tertiary at 29%, primary at 15% and unknown at 4.1%
    • 

  • default - only 1.8% of clients have credit in default
    • 

  • housing - 56% of clients have a housing loan
    • 

  • loan - 84% of clients have a personal loan
    • 

  • contact - majority of contact used cellular (64%), with 28% unknown and telephone at 6.4%
    • 

  • month - the last contact with clients was mostly done in May (30%) followed by July (15%), August (13%) and June 11%. The least contacts were made in the month of December 4.7%, probably due to less staff over the december break
    • 

  • poutcome - Outcome of previous marketing campaign is mostly unkown (81.7%), with failure at 10.8%, Other 4% and Success the lowest outcome at 3.3 %
    • 

  • Target - 88.3% of clients subscribed to a term deposit
    •

BoxPlot Multi-variate Analysis¶
    

  • Independent varibles: age, balance, duration campaign, pdays, previous - there exists a lot of outliers irregardless of whether Target variable is no or yes
    • 

  • Duration: clients who subscribed to term deposit (Target=yes), had a higher last contact duration Inter Quartile Range (Q1, Q2, Q3) compared to those who didn't. That means the longer a contact duration is the more interest shown and higher chances of subscription from the client
    • 

  • pdays: clients who subscribed to term deposit (Target=yes), had the same pdays Lower Quartile (Q1) and Median (Q2) as those who didnt. However those who subscribed to term deposit had a higher Upper Quartile (Q3) than those who didn't, meaning pdays can possibly predict roughly 50% of subscribers who take the term deposit
    •

Bi-variate analysis using Distplot and Crosstab¶
    

  • job: student and retired types of jobs have higher percentage of clients (28.7% & 22.8% respectively) that take the term deposit against those who don't. Blue-collar & entrepreneur have lower percentage of clients (7.2% & 8.2% respectively) that take the term deposit against those who don't probably because they have diversified investment portfolios
    • 

  • education: the more advanced the education, the higher percentage of that group that subscribe to term deposit. Unknown education has a percentage between that of secondary and tertiary, probably meaning these people have a street smart education and/or choose not to share their data
    • 

  • marital: single people are more likely to subscribe to term deposit (15%) followed by divorced (11.9%) and lastly married (10.1%) probably due to less demanding budget
    • 

  • housing: clients without housing loan have higher percentage of those who subscribe to term deposit vs those who don't have housing, probably due to attempt to increase credit profile
    • 

  • loan: clients without personal loan have higher percentage of those who subscribe to term deposit vs those who don't have housing, probably due to overcommitted credit profile
    • 

  • default: 6.3% of clients with credit in default subscribed to term deposit vs those who didn't. 11.8% of clients without credit in default subscribed to term deposit vs thos who didn't subscribe, that is double that of clients with credit in default
    • 

  • month: the last contact months that had the highest success vs non-success of clients subscribing to term deposit are March, September, October, and December, with over 40% success within that month
    • 

  • contact: clients with a contact communication type cellular/telephone had higher chances of subscribing to term deposit vs not subscribing, compared to unkown contact type, probably due to capability to communicate effectively
    •

def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):

    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,  fmt='.0f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )

Conclusion about the best algorithm¶
    

  • This project is based on predicting clients that are likely to subscribe to a term deposit, hence F1-Score (that measures a test's accuracy w.r.t recall and precision) is the most important, followed by Recall (accurately predicted outcome among actual positives), followed by Precision (did not label a sample as positive which was negative) and lastly Accuracy
    • 

  • Ensemble algorithms performed better than non-Ensemble algorithms in terms of accuracy and F1-Score, as expected, because of the voting mechanisms
    • 

  • Within Ensemble algorithms, boosting algorithms performed better than Bagging (XGBoost& CatBoost beating RandomForest & Bagging F1-Scores), which was expected due to the algorithm assigning weights to earlier poorly predicted entries, later on in its sequential action on data
    • 

  • Boosting - it is also probable that after tuning the other boosting algorithms (GradientBoost, AdaBoost), they might perform better than Bagging
    • 

  • Decision Trees generally overfit training data, however it came out as Number 3, due to tuning parameters to min_samples_leaf=5,splitter='best',max_leaf_nodes=190
    • 

  • Logistic Regression came out last, probably due to the overfitting and multi-colinearity
    • 

  • XGBoost is the best algorithm, with the most feature importance in descending order being: duration, balance, day, pdays, campaign
    • 

  • Therefore the best models in order are:
    • 
















    

  1. XGBoost
    2. 

  2. CatBoost
    3. 

  3. RandomForest
    4.

    5. 

  5. Bagging

Conclusion on voting on all algorithms¶
    

  • Voting results in the best precision (0.679834), better than individual algorithms
    • 

  • However voting results in less than average F1-Score (0.5115374) & Recall (0.410031). This is not ideal for financial services company who need an improved recall of those who would have potentially opened a term deposit account
    •
